# Atomic Commits — Small and Focused

## Golden Rule

**Each commit must be a single logical change. If you did two tasks, make two separate commits.**

---

## Why Small Commits Help

- **Easier code review:** Small, focused commits make it clear what changed and why for other developers.
- **Precise rollbacks:** If a bug is introduced, you can revert only the faulty commit without losing a whole day of work.
- **Organized history:** Clear, concise messages make it easier to navigate and maintain the codebase long term.
- **Faster bug hunting:** Finding the source of a problem is quicker when each commit focuses on one feature or change.
- **Continuous integration:** Frequent, small commits reduce merge conflicts between team members.

---

## Practices

- Prefer several small commits over one large "everything" commit.
- One feature or one fix per commit; avoid mixing unrelated changes.
- Keep the working tree buildable (and ideally tests passing) after each commit when possible.
- Use Conventional Commits (see 09-commits.mdc) for type, scope, and message format.
